> "The UN estimates that worldwide, four billion people live without basic access to justice."

This estimate comes from the [UN Commission on Legal Empowerment of the Poor](https://www.un.org/ruleoflaw/blog/document/making-the-law-work-for-everyone-vol-1-report-of-the-commission-on-legal-empowerment-of-the-poor/
).

> "Right now, in the United States, in India, in Slovenia, people like Ravi are raising their children in the shadow of factories or mines that are poisoning their air and their water. There are environmental laws that would protect these people, but many have never seen those laws, let alone having a shot at enforcing them."

In the United States, the four-part National Public Radio series [Poisoned Places: Toxic Air, Neglected Communities](https://www.npr.org/series/142000896/poisoned-places-toxic-air-neglected-communities
) sheds light on the impact of pollution in communities left outside of the protection of environmental regulations. In Slovenia, it took over a decade of activism by a local environmental group, [Eko Krog](https://www.goldmanprize.org/recipient/uros-macerl/), before a hazardous facility burning petcoke and waste was shut down. In India, [Calling the Bluff: Revealing the state of Monitoring and Compliance of Environmental Clearance Conditions](http://iced.cag.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/Calling-the-Bluff-final-PDF.pdf) analyzes company self-reports to reveal massive enforcement gaps in environmental regulation.

> "In many cities, 90 percent of the landlords in housing court have attorneys, while 90 percent of the tenants do not."

Matthew Desmond cites this statistic in his Pulitzer-winning book, [*Evicted: Poverty and Profit in the American City*](http://evictedbook.com/books/evicted-tr
), which portrays the housing crisis in the United States and the impact it has on poor people in Milwaukee.

> "Normally in New York, one out of nine tenants brought to housing court gets evicted. Researchers took a look at 150 cases in which people had help from these paralegals, and they found no evictions at all, not one."

These findings are from a [study](https://www.wnyc.org/story/tenants-housing-court-study-finds-navigators-can-be-good-alternatives-lawyers/
) by Rebecca Sandefur and Thomas Clarke called Roles Beyond Lawyers: Evaluation of the New York City Court Navigators Program.
